</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7BFFECFF76FEA4FD1CFEDC" blockId="78.[151,1437,290,532]" box="[151,764,290,317]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
Size. Maximum size 
<quantity id="2E379B383F7BFFECFE65FEA4FE30FEDD" box="[388,464,290,317]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" unit="cm" value="9.5">9.5 cm</quantity>
total length (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F7BFFEDFF26FEC0FC16FEA3" lastPageId="79" lastPageNumber="80" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7BFFECFF26FEC0FDB3FDF5" blockId="78.[151,1437,290,532]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
Morphology. D VI (VI–VII) + I,10–12;A I,9–12; P 18–21 (Miller 1986). Medium-sized goby with subcylindrical body, laterally compressed towards caudal fin, head slightly depressed and moderately large. Snout moderately large and pointed. Eyes dorsolateral, interorbital space quite narrow. Caudal peduncle long and slender, clearly lower than body depth. Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin with more or less rounded margin and no elongated spines. Caudal fin rounded. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7BFFECFDA3FE53FADEFE0E" bold="true" box="[578,1342,469,496]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Scales present on body and on predorsal area at least posteriorly</emphasis>
, usually visible on photographs at least dorsally.
</paragraph>
<caption id="BDB066553F7BFFECFF76F9DDFB5CF976" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601769" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6601769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601769/files/figure.png" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" startId="78.[151,250,1627,1651]" targetBox="[189,1397,556,1603]" targetPageId="78">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7BFFECFF76F9DDFB5CF976" blockId="78.[151,1436,1627,1688]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7BFFECFF76F9DDFEC1F992" bold="true" box="[151,289,1627,1651]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">FIGURE 67.</emphasis>
Live coloration in its natural habitat of 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7BFFECFD20F9DDFC5FF992" box="[705,959,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F7BFFECFD20F9DDFC5BF992" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Pallas" baseAuthorityYear="1770" box="[705,955,1627,1651]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">Pomatoschistus minutus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
A) Espiguette sand bank, Gulf of Lion, South France, Mediterranean, photo by T. Menut. B) Stavanger, Norway, Atlantic Ocean, photo by R. Svensen.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7BFFECFF26F943FDE5F83D" blockId="78.[151,1437,1733,2012]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
Live coloration. Background color pale with irregular reticulation and light brown, white or gray spots. Usually light colored with no recognizable pattern (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F7BFFECFD60F96FFD02F8E5" box="[641,738,1769,1796]" captionStart="FIGURE 67" captionStartId="78.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,556,1603]" captionTargetId="figure-139@78.[189,1397,556,1603]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURE 67. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Pomatoschistus minutus. A) Espiguette sand bank, Gulf of Lion, South France, Mediterranean, photo by T. Menut. B) Stavanger, Norway, Atlantic Ocean, photo by R. Svensen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601769/files/figure.png" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Fig. 67a</figureCitation>
), but sometimes with more contrasting markings: 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7BFFECFAFBF96FFDEBF8C6" bold="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">7, often illdefined whitish dorsal saddles,</emphasis>
the first, narrower and often fainter than the others, on nape above pectoral-fin base, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7BFFECFF36F8B7FE08F8AA" bold="true" box="[215,488,1841,1867]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">2 below first dorsal-fin</emphasis>
, 2 below second dorsal fin, 2 on caudal peduncle (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F7BFFECFBC2F8B7FB98F8AD" box="[1059,1144,1841,1868]" captionStart="FIGURE 67" captionStartId="78.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,556,1603]" captionTargetId="figure-139@78.[189,1397,556,1603]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURE 67. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Pomatoschistus minutus. A) Espiguette sand bank, Gulf of Lion, South France, Mediterranean, photo by T. Menut. B) Stavanger, Norway, Atlantic Ocean, photo by R. Svensen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601769/files/figure.png" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
); variable number of faint brown spots and vertical lines along midline, with one horizontal darker horizontal T-shaped blotch on caudal-fin base. One suborbital dark bar, often obvious, between eye and side of upper lip. No pale dot on nape behind eyes. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7BFFECFF76F81BFE67F83A" bold="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">First dorsal fin poorly pigmented, often with a blue-black spot on the distal rear corner, close to the edge, including in females</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F7BFFECFE77F847FE19F83D" box="[406,505,1985,2012]" captionStart="FIGURE 67" captionStartId="78.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,556,1603]" captionTargetId="figure-139@78.[189,1397,556,1603]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURE 67. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Pomatoschistus minutus. A) Espiguette sand bank, Gulf of Lion, South France, Mediterranean, photo by T. Menut. B) Stavanger, Norway, Atlantic Ocean, photo by R. Svensen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601769/files/figure.png" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Fig. 67b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7AFFEDFF26FF11FC16FEA3" blockId="79.[151,1436,151,322]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F7AFFEDFE9EFF11FD5FFF51" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[383,703,151,177]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marmoratus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7AFFEDFE9EFF11FD5FFF51" box="[383,703,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Pomatoschistus marmoratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F7AFFEDFD2CFF11FCA5FF51" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Kroyer" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[717,837,151,177]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7AFFEDFD2CFF11FD3EFF51" box="[717,734,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7AFFEDFD0DFF11FCA5FF51" box="[748,837,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F7AFFEDFCB2FF11FC0EFF51" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Collett" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[851,1006,151,177]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="norvegicus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7AFFEDFCB2FF11FC84FF51" box="[851,868,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7AFFEDFC92FF11FC0EFF51" box="[883,1006,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">norvegicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Habitat. Infralittoral and circalittoral species, on soft bottoms from less than 
<quantity id="2E379B383F7AFFEDFBC0FF3DFB96FF34" box="[1057,1142,187,213]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.55" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" unit="m" value="35.5" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="1.0">1–70 m</quantity>
depth (Miller 1986). Geographic distribution. Atlantic, Mediterranean and Black Sea. Recorded in the Mediterranean along the north coast from the Alboran Sea to Aegean Sea (Miller 1986; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F7AFFEDFCFBFE82FC3AFEFC" author="Ozen, O. &amp; Irmak, E." box="[794,986,259,287]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="161 - 164" refId="ref62320" refString="Ozen, O., Irmak, E. &amp; Bilecenog ˘ lu, M. (2007) Occurrence of Pomatoschistus minutus (Pallas, 1770) (Pisces: Gobiidae) at the north Aegean coast of Turkey. Annales, Series Historia Naturalis, 17, 161 - 164." type="journal article" year="2007">
Özen 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7AFFEDFCBCFE85FC6FFEFC" box="[861,911,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
), also common in the Black Sea (Miller 1986). In the Atlantic Ocean known from 
